"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-01-olympics-viewers-stunned-woman-flashes-tennis-match-21339814\", \"text\": \"Olympicsviewers were left stunned after a woman flashed the camera during a tennis match.  The incident occurred during the women's singles quarter-final betweenIga Swiatekand Danielle Collins on Wednesday night.  Spectators in the arena were performing a Mexican wave during a break in play between the two players.  Follow Metro.co.uk's live blog for updates from the Paris 2024 Olympics  The camera then stopped a man, woman and child, who were sat in the stands.  All three smiled and waved to the camera before the woman lifted up her top to show her bikini.  A fan who saw the footage on X wrote: 'Having a nice family outing at the Olympics and then Mum had to show her boobs again.'  Another user wrote: 'Bizarre behaviour with a young child.'  On the court, the match saw abust-up between the two players with Collins branding Swiatek as 'insincere'.  Collins told Swiatek to 'play at the server's pace' after the world No.1 held up her hand to halt the American's service motion.  Collins then appeared to hit Swiatek with the ball, while the Pole was jeered by fans for taking a long break at the end of the second set.  The American, Collins, who stopped playing in the third set because of an injured stomach muscle, retired from the match, handing the victory to Swiatek.  'I told Iga she did not have to be insincere about, you know, my injury,' Collins said.  'There is a lot that happens on camera, and there are a lot of people with a ton of charisma and come out and are one way on camera and another way in the locker room.  'And I just have not had the best experience, and I do not really feel like anybody needs to be insincere. They can be the way that they are. I can accept that, and I do not need the fakeness.'  For more stories like this,check our sport page.  Follow Metro Sport for the latest news onFacebook,TwitterandInstagram.  ArrowMORE:Imane Khelif fires warning to Olympic opponents after making boxer quit  ArrowMORE:The internet is going to extreme lengths to date Paris 2024 athletes  ArrowMORE:Why USA think they are top of the Olympics medal table - when they are not  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"